[Regarding the 1st article, from Canada:
This is a phenomenally heartbreaking piece about the neurological form of equine herpesvirus. The available vaccine does not prevent, or even lessen, the effects of the neurological form of this disease.

It is heartbreaking in the sense that no one seems to be working on a vaccine. Pets, large or small, or livestock of any form are important to their owners. Horses are often classified as companion animals and, indeed, some horses assist some individuals as service animals. Caring for animals evokes tremendous emotions, and the loss of one is very painful and emotionally distressing. As many horse owners have lost horses to this horrible disease, it is incredible there is no word of a company, research group, or government entity tackling this horrible disease. It seems that horse owners' pleas and cries for someone to tackle this disease fall on deaf ears.

This is a great story in taking biosecurity seriously. This manager/owner/horse lover is doing everything right: preventing contact with ill horse, showering, changing clothes and boots between barns or groups of horses, and likely taking temperatures of the animals. She expresses great empathy in not wanting her situation to happen to anyone else.

The old adage of "don't track it back" takes on new meaning here, as possibly a trainer who failed to take proper personal biosecurity measures after caring for an ill horse tracked the disease to this facility. If no other horses have been to the property in over a month, then it seems likely this disease rode in on a person.

Concerning both articles:
Biosecurity can be taken one step farther. Tire washes of vehicles can be done, especially if a vehicle is going into a pasture.

Biological security of a premises is huge and is no easy task and requires hypervigilance all the time, 24/7. Diseases never sleep. Neither should measures to protect yourself and your animals.

Hopefully -- wishfully -- someone will soon develop a vaccine to prevent the neurological form of this nasty disease. - Mod.TG

